          <td bgcolor="" valign="top" width="1"><img src="/magination/gfx/trans_header1.gif" width="22" height="2" vspace="0" hspace="0" border="0"></td>
          <td bgcolor="" valign="top"><!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2" bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
        <tr>
          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chpurple"><font class="h1font"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> How to use Sorreah<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/magination/gfx/star3.gif" width="21" height="22" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9003'>Shane "Bluntaxe" Reeves</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=9003&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> January 23, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> How to use Sorreah (Previously posted upon my homepage)<br>
<br>
Sorreah is one of the most versatile Magi available as he (yes it&#39;s a guy) can work in<br>
many decks, however he is not easy to play effectively. His power simply negates<br>
the opponent&#39;s Magi&#39;s power. Simply put you end up in a Magi battle with two Magi<br>
that have no text on them. Sorreah&#39;s starting energy isn&#39;t anything special and has<br>
the standard energize of five. Thus facing an opponent with a large energy supply<br>
can mean death for Sorreah. To counter this you have to prepare ahead of time by<br>
deciding where to put him in the deck and how to use his second strong-point, his<br>
starting cards.<br>
<br>
Sorreah as the starting Magi:<br>
Starting with Sorreah is tricky but can be well worth it. He doesn&#39;t start with any<br>
creatures so if you plan on having Sorreah in the starting position be sure that<br>
creatures make up half your deck, if not more. Putting Sorreah in the starting<br>
position helps against any of the energize four (or less) Magi. Those Magi usually<br>
rely upon their powers and effects to boost their loss of energy. The popular choice<br>
of putting Evu in the front position will be destroyed in no time as he loses his extra<br>
cards that the deck was relying upon. O&#39;qua another popular starting Magi also<br>
loses her ability to find Giant Parathin and run away. Also Magi that activate effects<br>
upon defeat lose out. Mobis is a prime example as he is often used to boost Trug. If<br>
Sorreah defeated Mobis, not only would Trug lose out on the extra three energy he<br>
also couldn&#39;t activate his power if he did manage to get the energy. So you see how<br>
having Sorreah to start out with can put the opponent at a disadvantage right<br>
away. <br>
<br>
Sorreah as the last Magi:<br>
Chances are if you use Sorreah as your starting Magi you won&#39;t be facing the last<br>
Magi with him (at least against better players). So a second field of thought on<br>
Sorreah is to use him as your last Magi to be more likely to face your better<br>
opponent&#39;s last (or sometimes second) Magi. In this case he great against Magi<br>
such as Gogor and Valkan who or even Eidon who appear as a last blast Magi,<br>
using their abilities (usually combines with saved up cards) to wipe you out and<br>
regain the upper hand. Sorreah of course negates all hope for these last ditch efforts.<br>
Another added benefit (albeit small) to using Sorreah last is deck secrecy. Using<br>
Sorreah last you run a chance to keep him hidden until you face an opponent good<br>
enough to get that far (hopefully in the finals ;). <br>
<br>
Sorreah&#39;s starting spells:<br>
The next thing you want to look at when using Sorreah are his starting cards. The<br>
obvious choice everyone is going to look at is Shockwave. While this is a decent<br>
choice and great to have early in the game (if you use him as your starting Magi) it<br>
may not be the choice for your current opponent. If you use Sorreah as your first<br>
Magi with a deck containing a lot of creatures, try using Cry of Thunder. Cry of<br>
Thunder is an excellent choice as it lets you get on the offensive right away. Allow<br>
yourself to go first just so you can get some creatures in play fast and ready your<br>
attack for turn two (getting warriors boots and another creature at the end of your<br>
first turn only helps this). If you also grab a Shockwave as your other starting card<br>
your opponent will be probably only play low energy creatures to avoid losing a lot of<br>
energy. Now using Sorreah as your last Magi works a little different (Sorreah as your<br>
second Magi works about the same). Now you have a chance to judge the<br>
battle-field before selecting your starting cards. Are you playing against Naroom with<br>
a bunch of high energy creatures? Grab the two Shockwaves! Playing against a Cald<br>
deck? You better grab a Tranquility! Have a Xyx elder in your hand? Grab a Shooting<br>
Star! Eidon sitting there with with an attack force you&#39;re not ready to handle? Grab<br>
the Eclipse! <br>
<br>
No matter where you put Sorreah you have to look out for any Magi that has a high<br>
energize rate, this will force Sorreah to work a bit more for the win, try to select the<br>
best combination of starting cards to defeat these Magi. Also when constructing<br>
your deck, and using Sorreah, don&#39;t be afraid to put at least one of those situation<br>
spells such as Storm Cloud or Eclipse. Having the right spell can mean the<br>
difference between life and death for Sorreah. <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php?id=3190&view=1'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/magination/main/join.php'> become a registered member</a></font></td></tr></table></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
